{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642902"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:45:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:45:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17970"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17970"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.09,0.04,0.61,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10684"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63851"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24884"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe trigeminal nerve has three divisions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly matches each division of the trigeminal nerve with the foramen it exits through?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["V1 = foramen rotundum; V2 = foramen ovale; V3 = superior orbital fissure","V1 = foramen rotundum; V2 = superior orbital fissure; V3 = foramen ovale","V1 = foramen ovale; V2 = foramen rotundum; V3 = superior orbital fissure","V1 = superior orbital fissure; V2 = foramen rotundum; V3 = foramen ovale","V1 = foramen ovale; V2 = superior orbital fissure; V3 = foramen rotundum"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe trigeminal nerve (CN V) is responsible for sensation in the face and motor functions such as biting and chewing. It has three divisions: ophthalmic (V1), maxillary (V2), and mandibular (V3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EV1\u003C/strong\u003E, the ophthalmic division, exits the skull through the \u003Cem\u003Esuperior orbital fissure\u003C/em\u003E. This division is responsible for sensation in the forehead and upper eyelid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EV2\u003C/strong\u003E, the maxillary division, exits through the \u003Cem\u003Eforamen rotundum\u003C/em\u003E. It provides sensation to the cheek, upper lip, and upper teeth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EV3\u003C/strong\u003E, the mandibular division, exits through the \u003Cem\u003Eforamen ovale\u003C/em\u003E. It supplies sensation to the lower jaw and motor function to the muscles of mastication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the exit points of these divisions is crucial for diagnosing and managing conditions like trigeminal neuralgia, which can cause facial pain in the distribution of one or more of these divisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ophthalmic division (V1) of the trigeminal nerve exits through the superior orbital fissure.","The maxillary division (V2) of the trigeminal nerve exits through the foramen rotundum.","The mandibular division (V3) of the trigeminal nerve exits through the foramen ovale."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics of North America, 49(1), 9\u201320. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.otc.2015.09.001","Anderson, B. W., Kortz, M. W., Black, A. C., \u0026 Al Kharazi, K. A. (2023). Anatomy, Head and Neck, Skull. In StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63851"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17970"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63851"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T08:39:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T08:40:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10684"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78510"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api